U0z8wLEy948A8OgPVNKDChCfoJuxXnSRSJonCnzmA0Jt8FR8lr4SBGD9uaidw==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Reviewing Gradle test task**\\n\\nI’ve got the Gradle test task set in the working directory as the project directory by default, which is good. I’m noticing a concern regarding hardcoding the artifact version in normal test inputs or assertions. It seems like we didn't hardcode it, which is a positive point. I should keep an eye on this to ensure we maintain best practices throughout the project. It's all about staying consistent!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented focused coverage for `org.scalatest.tools.DiscoverySuite$`.\n\nAdded:\n\n- `tests/src/org.scalatest/scalatest-core_3/3.2.19/src/test/scala/org_scalatest/scalatest_core_3/DiscoverySuiteTest.scala`\n\nThe new test drives ScalaTest discovery through the public `Runner` API with `-R` and `-w`, using:\n\n- a plain discoverable `Suite` to exercise:\n  - `ClassLoader#loadClass`\n  - `Class#newInstance`\n- a `@WrapWith` target plus wrapper suite to exercise:\n  - `Class#getDeclaredConstructors`\n  - `Constructor#newInstance`\n\nIt keeps the test scoped to the active dynamic-access class and avoids direct reflection in the test. I did not run tests, per the workflow instruction.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0485df7b70c835c30169fa766e89d8819da66add9239d9babb\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 672, "output": 1360, "cacheRead": 44032, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 46064, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1778021980536, "responseId": "resp_0485df7b70c835c30169fa765d41f0819db8ba94a6b99feb96"}}
